Bit pricey, but I can understand as the ingredients looked fresh. Great flavors, cute takeout bowl, and overall great service. Will definitely be coming in again if my work takes me near here again!

Donburi is an amazing fast casual restaurant. I got the Ebi Katsudon. The shrimp was perfectly tender and had a nice crunch along with the delicious Donburi sauce. The atmosphere is down-to-earth and the staff are up beat and nice. A great spot with good eats!

The name of the place really says it all - - they've got lots of varieties of Japanese rice bowls. It's a small place, maybe a dozen seats at a long bar. Although it was a busy lunchtime, our food came within about 5 minutes. I had a curry bowl with fried chicken and shrimp, with 3 varieties of pickled radish mixed in. As the Japanese say, "oishi!" (yummy).

I had the popular moriwase combo rice bowl. No tuna or yellowtail as advertised, just salmon as fish which is obviously farmed fish. At 20 dollars price point, I'd rather spend 10 more dollars and get an proper entree elsewhere. Lots and lots rice of course. The shrimp and the chicken was properly fried. Eel was regular old eel. Wasabi was freshly grated root. Of all the things served on the bowl, my favorite was after all fried chicken. Spicy mayo was good. Why am I giving this a 3 stars? Go to Chiko DC and get the salmon bowl for instance, you'll know what I mean. 3 dollars cheaper and much more interesting dish. Stick with something more traditional.

Donburi nails the simple experience at its 15-person bar, quick service, easy menu, and delicious food. You can watch your chef cook and assemble your simple Japanese rice bowl topped with pork, shrimp, salmon, etc., as well as a variety of other toppings that make for a simple - yet still complex - meal.  And in a city full of lavish meals and long waits, Donburi keeps the costs down and makes a delicious meal in minutes. Despite the limited seating, the seats do turn over quick, so don't get discouraged if there's a wait. I've walked in multiple times and the standing room area has been full, but I've always been seated within 10 minutes.

I visited the store two times within a single day and tried the don with salmon and eel. To be short: if you haven’t done any Japanese don before, you can have a try. If you looking for some authentic Don... Donburi is probably not the right place.  Pros: - Good service - Reasonable Price - The salmon and eel is really decent  Cons: - No sushi soy sauce (or less sodium soy sauce) available at all. I think for an authentic don store there should be sushi soy sauce available. Normal soy sauce is too salty for salmon don and it hurts the taste - The eel is too sweet even in 関東 style. I will regard it as a “change” for American food

food was okay, may have been great of oil had been changed. could tell it was old and burning.  very small space, so skip popular nights or get to go. fantastic service.
Sat down for 15 minutes before someone asked if i wanted to order. They weren't busy, guess they didn't want my business. I just got up and left. The two behind the counter didn't seem to mind.

Amazing ramen! Only 1 option for vegetarians, but it was so good I'd definitely go back! The food size was definitely generous, and we had some leftovers. They work well as leftovers thankfully. The food was really good with tofu and it came out fast. There's almost no space in there, so either get a seat ahead of time or get take out.
Delicious curry bowl

I had the mixed katsudon and oh man it was delicious! The sauce, toppings, all the flavors went really well together. Also it was suuuuper filling. Loved the minimalistic/simple seating and interior design but it definitely gets crowded quickly, so plan to wait a little bit if you're dining in.

Killed it, yet again.  A must stop for my trips to D.C. and the only place I would go for Donburi on the East Coast.  The sauce is the key, so delicious and really sets it apart.  Anyone can fry an egg, cook some rice, and deep fry tonkatsu but this place puts that delicious sauce in there an BAM!, I get a foodie boner every time.
Tasty rice bowls you won't regret. Pricey, but worth it.
I didn't expect this to be a mind blowing experience. I walked in thinking it was a sushi spot. However, the broiled eel certainly made up for the sushi disappointment.
My favorite restaurant in DC! We need more like this.

This place got good donburi. I like their katsu don and salmon sashimi don. But it is difficult to get a seat especially for more than 2 people. And the service is somewhat similar to a typical take-out restaurant in big cities. Transactional.

Great place for Japanese curry and rice bowls. I haven't eaten in the store but do get takeout from here regularly and everything has been great each time. My only recommendation would be for them to offer the Japanese curry sauce on the side

Lots of flavor. So much that some dishes lack balance. Half way through a bowl can be very salty with multiple super flavorful ingredients competing and never letting up. I recommend any dish with shashimi (insanely good alone) which adds something fresh to balance the heaviness of other components. Could just be my taste. This place is a gem, worth the money, just be careful if you don't dig heavy savory and salty on some dishes.  The service is fantastic, chefs are two feet from you and friendly. A great experience as well as meal.
Quite literally a hole in the wall -- the only seating is around the bar where the food is made. Delicious rice bowls and a fun place to go with a friend or on a date!

One of the best rice bowls places I have been to! The sashimi just melts in your mouth and both the chicken and shrimp katsudon are to die for! The portion sizes are perfect and are reasonably priced ($11) and you can always get sides if you need more meat. The service is really great and everyone is so nice,  especially during my first time there where i got extra rice for free! Can't wait to go back!

Local, social, rice bar. Good food, with distinct flavors vs alternatives in the city. I've been twice, and I don't often become a repeat customer anywhere. Not remotely pretentious, but still just cozy enough.
Fast food counter service, pay at the front. Food was great. Fish wasn't amazing, but was very good. Fried chicken was tasty.

Delicious food! I've been twice and am planning to come back soon. Their gyudon and unigidon are to die for, as are their different katsudons. And you get to watch them prepare all the delicious food!
Love, love, love the 'Donburi Moriwase'! So delish, you 'll want to lick the bowl! Service is seriously only mediocre. A bit pricey not sure it can be justified.
Amazingly delicious.

Really enjoyed the japenese curry here.

This is some of my favorite food I've ever had in my life. We've visited DC twice and been to Donburi both times. I cannot recommend this place highly enough. The rice bowls are delicious and filling. The food is quick and fresh.

Great food, fast service.

The flavor of the Karaagedon haunts me. Everything I've tried here has been incredible. The cooks always offer more rice and are very friendly. Love the layout of the place and there is always good music playing.

Amazing Nipponese flavor! Great food, fast service, in an fast moving atmosphere you would expect from such a restaurant service Tonkatsudon, Sakedon, and other Japanese flavors.

Easily one of the best places in town for katsudon. While the place is small there is enough of a take out/dine in balance so I've never had to wait long. They cook it all in front of you, the food is delicious, and with complimentary tea what else do you want?
Great food.

Please learn to treat your customers better. Also, they were out of the two main dishes. They let multiple people cut right in front of us and they completely ignored us. My sister and I felt super unwelcome. When we explained we had been waiting and they had let people cut they didn't care at all. Just not good customer service. Had a Mix Curry Katsudon. Nothing bad to say about the food. It was perfectly acceptable at the price point, albeit nothing out of this world so I'm surprised by the rave reviews. The service however was where this place fell flat. Came in and the guy in the till said it would be a 15-20 minute wait which was fine as I was in no rush. He took my name to put on a waiting list. All fine. Over the next 10-15 minutes the place got a lot busier. After a while the incumbent diners began finishing up and leaving, but instead of working his way through the list of names he'd written down and seating these guests, this gentleman continued serving every other take out customer and uber driver that came in. It got to the point where there were only two people actually sat down dining and about 10 people waiting to be seated. At this point I politely suggested that it might make sense to seat those people (myself included) before serving new customers as we were actually blocking this guy from doing his job properly anyway. I was met with a short and in my opinion rude response and the employee then proceeded to seat 3 groups who had arrived after me before eventually coming around to seating me (1 group of 4, 2 groups of 2 before myself, a solo diner so not exactly hard to seat).
Perfect!

My first attempt to non sushi Japanese food. I didn't know what to expect. It is a very small restaurant and there might be possibilities that you can bulge your elbow into someone else. But the taste and the way the food is being made is different, great and makes you feel attracted to. It is essentially a Japanese food bowl restaurant and with plenty of options. A must try for someone who loves food.
